The prepared SCDs nanocomposite materials were characterized via TEM, XPS, FTIR and EDS mapping to confirm their structure and properties. The morphology of SCDs nanocomposite materials were observed via TEM. In Fig. 3
                        b, the SCDs nanocomposite materials showed no significant difference from the original SBA-15/560 (see Fig. 3a), but their light transmittance had changed slightly. The absence of CDs had been observed, indicating that the CDs were grafted into the pore channels rather than outside the pore channels. The most important thing is that the composite ordered the parallel-aligned pore channels. In order to further explore their structure, the composites were characterized by XPS, FT-IR and EDS mapping. As shown in Fig. 3c, C, O and Si elements were detected in XPS spectra of SBA-15/560 and SCDs. The high resolution XPS spectrum of O1s, SBA-15/560 (see Fig. 3d) were found around 531.2, 532.4 eV which were attributed to the Si–O and C–O [4], the peak at 535.4 eV corresponded to the adsorbed O2 [50]. Meanwhile, from the SCDs (see Fig. 3e), it can be seen that two peaks appeared around 531.4, 532.2 and 533.9 eV which were attributed to the Si–O, C–O and the adsorbed O2 [51,52]. However, an additional O–CO bonds peak appeared at 532.8 eV against the SBA-15/560, which was probably caused by O–CO bonds from CDs [47] (see Table 1
                        ). Moreover, no nitrogen was found in the XPS spectrum of SCDs composites which might be attribute to the low nitrogen content of CDs. As shown in FT-IR spectra of SBA-15/560 and SCDs (Fig. 3f), the characteristic peaks were observed at 1082,808 cm−1 for vibration of Si–O–Si [47], and a new absorption band at 2889 cm−1 might be caused by the stretching vibrations of C–H after the loading of so-prepared CDs. A weak peak appeared at 1213 cm−1, indicating that the hydroxyl group on the surface of the CDs reacted with the epoxy group to form –OH in different environments [39]. These two kinds of absorption band suggested that the carbon dots had been successfully grafted onto the SBA-15/560. As shown in Fig. 3g, the EDS mapping analysis revealed that Si, O, C and N elements are evenly distributed across the SCDs surface with the content being 52.53% (Si), 42.57% (O), 4.76% (C) and 0.05% (N) respectively. The presence of nitrogen further proved that CDs were assembled into mesoporous channels.
